{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011n1VKfnNoZUu9agirQ8n3q","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `ray-client` pod is just a pod that sleeps - it's NOT a Ray node (it doesn't run `ray start`). So it shouldn't be counted as a Ray node.\n\nBut then why does Ray status show 4 active nodes? Let me think:\n- Head node (1)\n- 2 new workers (2)\n- Old workers that crash-looped might have briefly registered before crashing, and Ray's GCS hasn't cleaned them up yet\n\nOR\n\n- The old worker's previous run might have been successful somehow (with 2 restarts, maybe one of those attempts succeeded briefly)\n\nThis is a timing issue - the 4th node will eventually drop off. \n\nLet me check the actual node IDs from the status output to see what's really running.\n\nSo there are 4 nodes active. With 2 workers that each restarted twice, some of those restart attempts could have briefly connected to Ray. But I need to think about what happens when `ray start` gets an unrecognized flag like `--bad-flag`. If argparse rejects it, the command fails immediately without registering any node. But if it issues a warning and continues, the node would register and then stay running because of the `--block` flag.\n\nGiven the crash-looping behavior, option 1 seems more likely. Let me wait and check the node count again to see if it's actually stable at 4.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":483,"cache_read_input_tokens":33812,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":483},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"169b2087-84d6-4dc1-9e41-6aa0db857c7f","uuid":"8389ebac-14b6-415c-92f2-b566e5ef1eec","request_id":"req_011CcRJiusspU6cwaCFuuM1p"}
