{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015EkzGuG3vGXy2XFSmWBNC5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Ray consistently shows 4 active nodes. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\nThe deployment has only:\n- 1 ray-head pod\n- 2 ray-worker pods\n- 1 ray-client pod (but that's just sleeping, not joined Ray)\n\nSo where is the 4th node coming from? Let me investigate more carefully. Maybe the ray-client pod actually ran ray start at some point, or maybe the precondition set up extra nodes.\n\nOr maybe the head node itself counts as a node (1) + 2 workers = 3, but there's 4...\nI'm wondering if there's a Ray process running outside the cluster, or if one of the crashing workers managed to connect before the bad flag caused it to fail. When `ray start` receives an unrecognized flag, it should exit immediately with an error rather than partially starting services. But I need to double-check the pod status more carefully—the pods showed `1/1 Running`, which suggests they're actually running.\n\nThe key insight is that `1/1 Running` with 2 restarts means the container is currently in its third attempt. Since `ray start --block --bad-flag` exits immediately, the pod briefly appears as Running before crashing. The readiness probe might not be configured, which would explain why the pod shows as Ready even though the process is about to fail.\n\nNow I need to look at the precondition.log to see what was actually set up and understand where that fourth node is coming from.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1200,"cache_read_input_tokens":36097,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1200},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"169b2087-84d6-4dc1-9e4